<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>Home Affairs phoned her and resolved the whole mess.Zandi said she could now get on with her plans to register her son for a social grant and send him to a creche.The mum from Schoemansdal in Mpumalanga told Daily Sun she gave birth to her son in 2014, but never realised he’d been classified as a girl until she was discharged from hospital.Since then it had been a difficult journey to get the error corrected.Zandi said despite several attempts to fill in new forms to get the birth certificate fixed, the local department could not help her.That was until she contacted Daily Sun.The SunTeam contacted spokesman for the department, Thabo Mokgola, and he took the details of the young mum and promised to follow up on the case. “When I got a call from the Home Affairs office in Tshwane I thought they were joking because I had lost all hope. There was no creche that was willing to admit my son,” said Zandi. “I’m glad my son will now finally be registered for a social grant and can go to creche – and it’s all thanks to Daily Sun!”